      "id":"environment/2013/nov/11/ed-davey-public-trust-energy-companies",
      "sectionId":"environment",
      "sectionName":"Environment",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-11T17:47:41Z",
      "webTitle":"Ed Davey: public trust in energy companies is breaking down",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/nov/11/ed-davey-public-trust-energy-companies",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/environment/2013/nov/11/ed-davey-public-trust-energy-companies",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"5",
        "trailText":"Energy secretary says the big suppliers face a 'Fred the Shred' moment as the public sees in them a reflection of bankers' greed",
        "headline":"Ed Davey: public trust in energy companies is breaking down",
        "body":"<p>Energy companies are facing a \"Fred the Shred\" moment because the public sees in them \"a reflection of the greed that consumed the banks\", the energy secretary, Ed Davey, will tell the industry on Tuesday.</p><p>Davey's linking of energy companies to <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fred_Goodwin\" title=\"\">Fred Goodwin</a>, the disgraced banker who led the Royal Bank of Scotland to collapse and a taxpayer bailout, raises the rhetoric of the heated and prolonged row over soaring energy bills to a new level.</p><p>In a speech at the annual conference of EnergyUK, which represents the industry, he will say: \"Trust between those who supply energy and those who use it is breaking down. It is so difficult for people to work out what exactly they are paying for, that they fear the big energy companies are taking them for a ride when bills go up.\"</p><p>He will claim: \"Fair or not, they look at the big suppliers and they see a reflection of the greed that consumed the banks. So this is a 'Fred the Shred' moment for the industry. You deliver an essential public service, so your industry must serve the public – and the public must have trust in what you do.\"</p><p>The comments follow accusations by Labour, which has pledged to freeze energy prices for 20 months if elected, that the government has failed to take the side of the consumer.</p><p>Davey will tell the industry that the UK needs profitable energy companies so that they can invest in replacing the nation's ageing and dirty power stations. But he will warn: \"Those profits cannot come at the expense of the elderly, the vulnerable, and the poorest in our society. Customers are not just cash cows to be squeezed in the pursuit of a higher return for shareholders.\"</p><p>EnergyUK has said the profit margins of the big six are about 5%. Critics accept that is likely to be accurate for the parts of the energy businesses supplying domestic customers, but say the profit margins for the electricity generation arms of the companies are much higher.</p><p>Davey will also addresses the controversy over the, government-imposed green levies that make up 9% of the average duel-fuel bill. \"We have opened up our books and we are looking at how we can reduce the impact of government policies on bills,\" he will say. However, there is deep confusion over which of the numerous green levies are being scrutinised under the review announced by David Cameron in October.</p><p>The prime minister along with the energy minister, Michael Fallon, have insisted all the levies – including both those that cut energy bills for pensioners and those claiming benefits and those to support renewable energy – could be cut. Davey, a Lib Dem, and the Conservative climate change minister, Greg Barker, have both insisted renewable energy subsidies are not part of the review.</p><p>Davey will challenge the big six to be more transparent about the profits they make in both their retail and generation arms. \"Our commitment [over green levies] must be matched by a commitment in industry to open up your books and set out exactly how you are bearing down on your own costs to make bills as low as possible.\" He will say the regulator Ofgem will have the government's full support in forcing greater transparency if necessary.\"</p><p>A <a href=\"http://press.which.co.uk/whichpressreleases/consumer-trust-in-the-energy-industry-hits-new-low/\" title=\"\">poll published on 3 October</a> by consumer group Which shows just 15% of the public trust energy companies to act in customers' best interest, down from 27% before recent above-inflation price rises, making energy the most distrusted of all consumer industry sectors.</p><p>In response to Davey's comments at the Energy UK Annual Conference, Energy UK said: \"The energy industry is already working hard to ensure everyone can keep the lights on and stay warm this winter. The best way to do this is for everyone to work together which is why this tit for tat Punch and Judy show of insults is so unproductive.</p><p>\"The energy industry is vital to the UK. It is  a major employer, a serious investor and a significant taxpayer. As analysis form UBS shows about 95 per cent of rising energy costs are out of the hands of the energy companies and can be attributed to government policies and other network, social and environmental costs.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/422224701|2013-11-13T15:47:59Z|e1603e483706d29c8ce11d0e651df451bda409da -->",
