      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-13T09:57:14Z",
      "webTitle":"SSE hikes shareholder payouts ahead of Friday's energy price rise",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/nov/13/sse-hikes-shareholders-payouts-energy-price-rises",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/business/2013/nov/13/sse-hikes-shareholders-payouts-energy-price-rises",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"SSE makes the case for higher bills amid rising costs, as it reveals a drop in customers and profits over the last six months",
        "headline":"SSE hikes shareholder payouts ahead of Friday's energy price rise",
        "body":"<p>Energy firm SSE has announced an inflation-busting dividend for shareholders just two days before it puts up customer bills by 8.2%.</p><p>SSE's dividend to shareholders will go up by 3.2% to 26p a share, a healthy return above the 2.2% inflation rate. On Friday SSE's 10 million customers – largely in Scotland and southern England – will see their bills going up well above inflation, taking the average dual-fuel bill to £1,380, in the same week that the National Audit Office warned of above-inflation energy bills until 2030.</p><p>SSE made the case for higher bills in its first-half results on Wednesday morning, which showed a 12% fall in adjusted pre-tax profits to £354m for the six months to the end of September, compared with £400m last year.</p><p></p><p>SSE said it made a £89.4m loss on its retail business of selling energy to customers, blaming higher wholesale gas prices, as well as rising environmental, social and distribution costs. The firm made a £455m profit from running energy networks and £160m on its wholesale business, which generates electricity, produces and stores gas.</p><p>SSE, which was fined a record £10.5m by regulator Ofgem earlier this year for \"prolonged and extensive mis-selling\", also revealed it had lost 60,000 customers over the period.</p><p>Company executives were forced on the defensive on Wednesday morning, insisting they put customers before shareholders.</p><p>Alan Young, managing director of corporate affairs at SSE, admitted that standards in the industry needed to improve. Speaking on BBC Radio 4's Today programme, he said: \"If we don't have a decent relationship with customers we will lose the mandate to run the business.\"</p><p>Young defended SSE's generous payouts to shareholders, after the company boasted in its latest annual report that it has paid above-inflation dividends every year since SSE was formed in 1998.</p><p>\"SSE is a good performer when it comes to paying dividends, but those dividends have got a purpose,\" he said. \"We want to make sure we are able to continue to attract the investment&nbsp;… that is needed to make sure the UK has secure energy supplies for many years to come.\"</p><p>The SSE chief executive, Alistair Phillips-Davies, told Radio 5 bills would be cut – \"no ifs, no buts\" – if the government's green levies were reduced. The big six energy companies have been calling on the government to shift the cost of green levies, which pay for free and subsidised home insulation, from their businesses to the taxpayer.</p><p>Hard-pressed customers face further bad news as Whitehall's spending watchdog warned of 17 years of rising utility bills, while in a separate report, UBS analysts have warned that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/nov/12/fuel-bill-increases-edf-big-six\" title=\"\">energy costs are set to rise by almost 50% by 2020</a>.</p><p>SSE kicked off the annual winter price hikes this year and has since been followed by British Gas, nPower, Scottish Power and EDF Energy – <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/10/sse-raises-prices-average-annual-bill\" title=\"\">generating a political furore over soaring energy bills</a>.</p><p>The climate change and energy secretary, Ed Davey, became the latest to join the chorus of condemnation on Tuesday when he accused the big six of using customers as \"<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/nov/11/ed-davey-public-trust-energy-companies\" title=\"\">cash cows to be squeezed in pursuit of higher returns for shareholders</a>\".</p><p>The Labour leader, Ed Miliband, former prime minister John Major and the archbishop of Canterbury Justin Welby have also weighed in against the energy companies, which the latest polls show are less trusted than banks and car salesman.</p><p>E.ON, the only one of the big six not to have announced a price rise, is reported to be planning to reveal a 6.6% price increase later this month.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/422367806|2013-11-13T15:47:59Z|238a308d5c4a1736548a8901f48b07595ece47c3 -->",
